<h1>Chapter 2
<br>Document Model Issues for Hypermedia</h1>
<p>
<hr width="80%">
</center>

 <H1>Media Items</H1> 
 <P><UL>
<LI><H2>It is a data object used as part of a presentation
</H2><ul><LI> Media items can be monomedium (single medium i.e. text or
sound) or composite (interlieved video and sound)</ul>
</UL><UL>
<LI><H2>Media items have data-type dependent properties such as,
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Most important property is in relation to time and space.
<UL>
<LI>text or graphics-spatial, no intrinsic temporal dimension
<LI>video or animation- spatial and temporal dimensions
<LI>sound-temporal But no spatial dimension
</UL></UL></UL><UL>
<LI><H2> Media items does not have to be a complete file or object
</H2>
<UL>
<LI>it can be reference to part of a physically stored object.<p> For
example: in case of text the object may be a complete object, where only a
section is used. In case of sound, a selection from a music item that
last few seconds. </UL></UL><UL> <LI><H2>Other media items that can be
included in a presentation are outputs
from external processes <font color=red>(real time sources)</font> such as,</h2> <ul> a video camera pointing at a
scene
outside, or reading from a monitoring device. We can still treat these as
objects with similar space dimensions, but they have indefinite time
dimensions. </UL></P>
<P></P> 



